<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-689-068  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 689 068.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Sept 11 1989 n555 p22(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Statistics weigh on NATO contractors. (measurements of NATO forcesin Europe affect weapons sales)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Van Nostrand, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Static and more-complex dynamic analyses of North Atlantic TreatyOrganization (NATO) military capabilities versus those of theWarsaw Pact give contrary views of their relative strengths.andP;  Theacceptance of one or the other analysis affects the manner inwhich the US and Western European governments negotiate weaponscontrol treaties, the governments' decisions to build up ordiminish their forces and their equipage, and their purchases ofadditional or new weapons systems.andP;  A static analysis tends toemphasize the numerical strength of the Warsaw Pact forces and,consequently, promote the buildup of NATO armaments.andP;  Dynamicanalyses use a variety of techniques to forecast the likelyoutcomes of battles between the two groups and generally suggestthat NATO forces are adequate, diminishing prospects for growingarms sales.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     North Atlantic Treaty OrganizationLikelihood of SurvivalMilitaryWeaponsWeapons Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Armament numbers look good for the Soviets. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>